\vspace{11pt}
\noindent Dear Professor Sheffield,

\vspace{11pt}
I'm an environmental scientist with several years experience working on research projects to assess the impact of environmental change on the water cycle. I'm applying for the position of Research Fellow in Hydrological Forecasting in order to address critical food and water security challenges in Saudi Arabia, Zambia and the U.S. while also using state of the art models and data to advance our understanding of hydrological processes and vegetation dynamics in dryland environments.

\vspace{11pt}
In my current position at the Centre for Water Systems I lead the University of Exeter contribution to CHANSE, an interdisciplinary project which studies the interactions and feedbacks between human activities, especially irrigation, on the hydrology of the Indo-Gangetic Plain. This project follows on from my PhD at Imperial College, where I developed tools and data products to quantify interactions between land surface processes across the IGP and the South Asian monsoon. Here are some highlights of my career so far:

\vspace{11pt}

\begin{itemize}
  \item I designed and built an open-source software package for land use change modelling (i.e. modelling processes such as urbanisation and deforestation) which has been used for research and education worldwide
  \vspace{0.1cm}

  \item I produced novel datasets showing land use change and agricultural intensification across the Indian subcontinent using a machine learning algorithm to predict the spatial allocation of land change
  \vspace{0.1cm}
    
  \item I used a process-based land surface model to show that intensive irrigation across the Indo-Gangetic Plain influences the behaviour of the South Asian monsoon
  \vspace{0.1cm}

  \item As a Research Assistant at Imperial College I developed a regional rainfall-runoff model to assess the contribution of glacier melt to water users in the tropical Andes
\end{itemize}

  \item I contributed to the development of a socio-hydrological model to study farmer behaviour in intensively irrigated rice-wheat systems, which we used to highlight key challenges around water security and farmer livelihood in the Indo-Gangetic Plain

\vspace{11pt}
As these highlights show, I have wide experience in hydrological modelling and data analysis for tackling food and water security challenges in developing countries. I have more limited experience in crop modelling, but over the last few months have been working on a spatially explicit implementation of the FAO AquaCrop model. I have strong scientific programming abilities in R, Python, C/C++ and Bash shell script and also have experience developing robust, well-documented software for other users. I'm familiar with various data formats including NetCDF and GDAL raster formats and routinely use command line tools and shell script to download and process large data sets. I have extensive experience using GRASS GIS, an open-source GIS, for data processing and hydrological modelling.

\vspace{11pt}
I would welcome the opportunity to discuss with you in person how my skills and research experience could benefit your research group.

\vspace{11pt}
Yours sincerely\\
Simon Moulds
